title: Jack Gosiewski
text:
Jack Gosiewski (; born 29 May 1994) is an Australian professional <a href="rugby%20league">rugby league</a> footballer who plays as a forward for the <a href="St.%20George%20Illawarra%20Dragons">St. George Illawarra Dragons</a> in the <a href="National%20Rugby%20League">NRL</a>. 
He previously played for the <a href="South%20Sydney%20Rabbitohs">South Sydney Rabbitohs</a> and <a href="Manly-Warringah%20Sea%20Eagles">Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles</a> in the <a href="National%20Rugby%20League">National Rugby League</a>.
Background.
Gosiewski was born in <a href="Murwillumbah">Murwillumbah, New South Wales</a>, Australia.
He played his junior rugby league for the <a href="Mullumbimby%20Giants">Mullumbimby Giants</a>, before being signed by the <a href="South%20Sydney%20Rabbitohs">South Sydney Rabbitohs</a>. Gosiewski is of Polish descent.
Playing career.
Early career.
In 2013 and 2014, Gosiewski played for the <a href="South%20Sydney%20Rabbitohs">South Sydney Rabbitohs</a>' <a href="National%20Youth%20Competition%20%28rugby%20league%29">NYC</a> team, captaining the side in 2014. In 2015, he graduated to their <a href="Intrust%20Super%20Premiership%20NSW">New South Wales Cup</a> team, <a href="North%20Sydney%20Bears">North Sydney Bears</a>. At the conclusion of the 2015 season, he played 18 games for North Sydney and scored 4 tries.
2016.
In round 10 of the <a href="2016%20NRL%20season">2016 NRL season</a>, Gosiewski made his <a href="National%20Rugby%20League">NRL</a> debut for South Sydney against the <a href="Parramatta%20Eels">Parramatta Eels</a>. He played a total of 5 games for South Sydney in 2016, for most of the season though, he featured for North Sydney, making 9 appearances and scoring 3 tries. In October, he re-signed with Souths on a one-year contract until the end of 2017.
2017.
Gosiewski spent most of the <a href="2017%20NRL%20season">2017 NRL season</a> out with a torn patella. After getting match fitness and game time with South Sydney's feeder club North Sydney, he was recalled to the South Sydney lineup and played his sole <a href="NRL">NRL</a> game of the season in South Sydney's 36-18 victory over the <a href="New%20Zealand%20Warriors">New Zealand Warriors</a>. After not being offered a new contract by Souths, he signed a one-year contract in September, with the <a href="Manly-Warringah%20Sea%20Eagles">Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles</a> starting in 2018.
2018.
Gosiewski made his debut for Manly in round 5 against the <a href="Gold%20Coast%20Titans">Gold Coast Titans</a>. Gosiewski featured in 8 games for Manly as the club endured a torrid 2018 season finishing second last on the table. Gosiewski resigned for the <a href="Manly%20Warringah%20Sea%20Eagles">Manly Warringah Sea Eagles</a> for another season, keeping him at the club until the end of 2019.
2019.
In round 22 of the <a href="2019%20NRL%20season">2019 NRL season</a> against <a href="Wests%20Tigers">Wests Tigers</a>, Gosiewski scored two tries as Manly-Warringah won the match 32-12 at <a href="Brookvale%20Oval">Brookvale Oval</a>.
Gosiewski played 19 games for Manly in the <a href="2019%20NRL%20season">2019 NRL season</a> as the club finished 6th on the table and qualified for the finals. Gosiewski played in both of Manly's finals matches and scored a try in the club's elimination final loss against <a href="South%20Sydney%20Rabbitohs">South Sydney</a> at <a href="ANZ%20Stadium">ANZ Stadium</a>.
2020.
In round 19 of the <a href="2020%20NRL%20season">2020 NRL season</a>, he scored two tries for Manly-Warringah in their 24-42 loss against the <a href="Gold%20Coast%20Titans">Gold Coast</a> at <a href="Brookvale%20Oval">Brookvale Oval</a>.
He played a total of 13 games for Manly-Warringah in the <a href="2020%20NRL%20season">2020 NRL season</a> as they finished a disappointing 13th on the table.
2021.
Gosiewski played six games for Manly in the <a href="2021%20NRL%20season">2021 NRL season</a>. On October 6, he was released by the Manly club. On October 15 Gosiewski signed a one-year deal with the <a href="St.%20George%20Illawarra%20Dragons">St. George Illawarra Dragons</a> for the 2022 season.
